crew maintains situational awareness.

264
00:20:28,289 --> 00:20:30,250
Knowing what is going on.

265
00:20:30,250 --> 00:20:34,499
Knowing there is another plane.

266
00:20:34,499 --> 00:20:38,559
All this information must be shared in the
team.

267
00:20:38,559 --> 00:20:40,830
Planning decision making should be shared.

268
00:20:40,830 --> 00:20:44,460
Although you have a single leader who makes
the decision.

269
00:20:44,460 --> 00:20:51,789
Every one is voiced their objections.

270
00:20:51,789 --> 00:20:57,070
Communication inside and outside the cockpit
are vital.

271
00:20:57,070 --> 00:20:59,740
And inside and outside the team.

272
00:20:59,740 --> 00:21:02,289
And good teamwork.

273
00:21:02,289 --> 00:21:06,019
Everyone gets on with the tasks they need
to.

274
00:21:06,019 --> 00:21:10,890
Rather than trying to get to do the same task.

275
00:21:10,890 --> 00:21:13,450
This isn't a leadership talk.

276
00:21:13,450 --> 00:21:23,740
This is a talk about a lot of people dying
a hideous death.

277
00:21:23,740 --> 00:21:26,990
Leading people is just one person's job.

278
00:21:26,990 --> 00:21:30,049
And effective teamwork is everybody's job.

279
00:21:30,049 --> 00:21:35,809
The entire team needs to be involved.

280
00:21:35,809 --> 00:21:45,690
So, crew management is taken on by United
in 1980, followed by talks by Nasa.

281
00:21:45,690 --> 00:21:48,970
In their Apollo program.

282
00:21:48,970 --> 00:21:57,740
It was thought this was going to help minimize
crew problems, failures.

283
00:21:57,740 --> 00:21:59,320
In the future.

284
00:21:59,320 --> 00:22:07,799
So, what happens if a crew faces what normally
would be a non survivable incident?

285
00:22:07,799 --> 00:22:12,280
They have excellent crew resource management.

286
00:22:12,280 --> 00:22:22,330
So, this would be United 232.

287
00:22:22,330 --> 00:22:28,740
On 19 July 1989, at 3.15 in the afternoon.

288
00:22:28,740 --> 00:22:31,850
Near Sioux City, Iowa.

289
00:22:31,850 --> 00:22:36,640
A 3-engined airliner.

290
00:22:36,640 --> 00:22:38,779
Was flying from Denver to Chicago.

291
00:22:38,779 --> 00:22:40,240
296 souls.

292
00:22:40,240 --> 00:22:49,559
An unusual number was children.

293
00:22:49,559 --> 00:22:56,390
After 3.15, the rear central engine blew.

294
00:22:56,390 --> 00:23:03,889
They fan, main turbine disk shattered into
several pieces.

295
00:23:03,889 --> 00:23:08,260
And the pieces went through the tailpipe assembly.

296
00:23:08,260 --> 00:23:14,769
What that left United 232 with was 2 problems.

297
00:23:14,769 --> 00:23:23,249
Firstly the aircraft had a tendency to turn
to the right because of the damage.

298
00:23:23,249 --> 00:23:26,690
Left alone it would flip itself over completely.

299
00:23:26,690 --> 00:23:30,690
You don't want to do that.

300
00:23:30,690 --> 00:23:33,120
That is not a major problem.

301
00:23:33,120 --> 00:23:35,441
You have the aircraft controls to compensate.

302
00:23:35,441 --> 00:23:39,250
Move it back.

303
00:23:39,250 --> 00:23:43,309
This would be a problem if they lost all the
hydrolics.

304
00:23:43,309 --> 00:23:45,240
Which they had.

305
00:23:45,240 --> 00:23:49,279
All 3 hydrolic systems were made inoperative.

306
00:23:49,279 --> 00:23:58,159
Each is driven by an engine.

307
00:23:58,159 --> 00:24:03,529
All of the hydrolic fluid drained out of the
system.

308
00:24:03,529 --> 00:24:10,619
The flight engineer on the radio says, this
is united 232.

309
00:24:10,619 --> 00:24:13,159
We blew nummer 2, we lost all hydraulics.

310
00:24:13,159 --> 00:24:20,570
We are only able to control with asymmetrical
power settings.

311
00:24:20,570 --> 00:24:27,360
They had no rudders or speed breaks or even
a little break on the wheels.

312
00:24:27,360 --> 00:24:30,879
Should they land.

313
00:24:30,879 --> 00:24:35,149
The maintenance then had a really interesting
amusing conversation.

314
00:24:35,149 --> 00:24:41,190
You still have 1 and 3?

315
00:24:41,190 --> 00:24:50,580
No, you have 1 and 2?

316
00:24:50,580 --> 00:24:56,090
This was calculated as being a 10 to the 9th
to 1 chance.

317
00:24:56,090 --> 00:25:04,429
The United have checklists for all, except
this one.

318
00:25:04,429 --> 00:25:09,169
It is deemed impossible and unsurvivable.

319
00:25:09,169 --> 00:25:12,820
The captain said, we are trying to go straight.

320
00:25:12,820 --> 00:25:16,440
We're not having much luck.

321
00:25:16,440 --> 00:25:20,470
The crew sorted out the engine problem.

322
00:25:20,470 --> 00:25:24,159
Within 14 seconds.

323
00:25:24,159 --> 00:25:28,299
It was then that they realised the plane wasn't
reacting.

324
00:25:28,299 --> 00:25:31,470
They started talking all 3 themselves.

325
00:25:31,470 --> 00:25:34,350
Every operation they were doing.

326
00:25:34,350 --> 00:25:36,799
Continue using the controls.

327
00:25:36,799 --> 00:25:43,750
In case it had effects.

328
00:25:43,750 --> 00:25:50,799
Everything they have to do is talk through
as an entire team before they make a decision.

329
00:25:50,799 --> 00:25:57,909
Haynes: We didn't do this thing on my last
performance check.

330
00:25:57,909 --> 00:26:02,360
Then something remarkable happens.

331
00:26:02,360 --> 00:26:04,900
This is real Hollywood moment.

332
00:26:04,900 --> 00:26:08,760
One of the passengers comes up to help.

333
00:26:08,760 --> 00:26:14,190
I'll introduce myself.

334
00:26:14,190 --> 00:26:18,549
The passenger introduces himself, Denny Fitch.

335
00:26:18,549 --> 00:26:26,059
He has been working for the last 3-4 weeks
as United DC 10 flight instructor.

336
00:26:26,059 --> 00:26:31,230
He is the 1 person that you really want in
the cockpit.

337
00:26:31,230 --> 00:26:33,399
This is in part.

338
00:26:33,399 --> 00:26:38,960
He is familiar with another crash.

339
00:26:38,960 --> 00:26:49,429
Japan Airlines 123.

340
00:26:49,429 --> 00:26:53,740
This is the most serious single incident air
disaster after.

341
00:26:53,740 --> 00:26:55,999
1985, 6.24.

342
00:26:55,999 --> 00:27:01,230
It is getting dark.

343
00:27:01,230 --> 00:27:03,830
The plane took off from Tokyo.

344
00:27:03,830 --> 00:27:11,919
A 747 short range which carries extra people.

345
00:27:11,919 --> 00:27:17,789
A tragedy in itself.

346
00:27:17,789 --> 00:27:25,610
As they flew upto altitude, a bad repair to
a bulkhead causes decompression.

347
00:27:25,610 --> 00:27:29,210
I shall use my laserpointer.

348
00:27:29,210 --> 00:27:31,809
Can you see there?

349
00:27:31,809 --> 00:27:35,100
There is a bit missing.

350
00:27:35,100 --> 00:27:40,570
The vertical stabilizor has been blown off.

351
00:27:40,570 --> 00:27:47,130
That has taken out all of the hydraulics.

352
00:27:47,130 --> 00:27:50,490
They managed 35 minutes of flight time.

353
00:27:50,490 --> 00:27:53,049
In a very unstable aircraft.

354
00:27:53,049 --> 00:27:57,340
They were not only missing control service.

355
00:27:57,340 --> 00:28:01,340
They were missing large chunks of the aircraft.

356
00:28:01,340 --> 00:28:06,659
They crashed in a remote area.

357
00:28:06,659 --> 00:28:12,480
Initial reports suggested no survivors.

358
00:28:12,480 --> 00:28:19,149
One of the 4 survivors they found the next
morning said that the heard the helicopter

359
00:28:19,149 --> 00:28:25,580
circling, see the lights and it flew off.

360
00:28:25,580 --> 00:28:31,909
All the moaning from the other survivors also
faded to nothing.

361
00:28:31,909 --> 00:28:32,909
As you might guess.

362
00:28:32,909 --> 00:28:36,830
This is the other one that really freaks me
out.

363
00:28:36,830 --> 00:28:40,070
Back to United 232.

364
00:28:40,070 --> 00:28:43,000
I'm looking shaky on time.

365
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:47,529
- They are also running late.

366
00:28:47,529 --> 00:28:48,529
- All right.

367
00:28:48,529 --> 00:28:52,570
In that case, I'll take ages!

368
00:28:52,570 --> 00:28:57,279
United 232.

369
00:28:57,279 --> 00:29:00,559
Haynes is in no illusions.

370
00:29:00,559 --> 00:29:05,049
He is talking to the cabin crew.

371
00:29:05,049 --> 00:29:10,369
I can't remember the name.

372
00:29:10,369 --> 00:29:13,840
She is talking about whether or not they are
going to evacuate.

373
00:29:13,840 --> 00:29:22,059
If we are at the front I'll tell you.

374
00:29:22,059 --> 00:29:26,460
He comments, won't this be a fun landing?

375
00:29:26,460 --> 00:29:32,509
The air crew talk about every decision.

376
00:29:32,509 --> 00:29:40,860
One of the decisions they talk about is how
and whether to lower the landing gear.

377
00:29:40,860 --> 00:29:45,460
An aircraft can land without a landing gear.

378
00:29:45,460 --> 00:29:49,409
On a soft surface it is preferably.

379
00:29:49,409 --> 00:29:58,120
Otherwise it will cause more damage.

380
00:29:58,120 --> 00:30:00,629
They decided unanimously to lower it.

381
00:30:00,629 --> 00:30:03,559
There are 2 mechanisms.

382
00:30:03,559 --> 00:30:06,830
They decide to crank it down.

383
00:30:06,830 --> 00:30:14,879
Which will release some extra hydraulic fluid.

384
00:30:14,879 --> 00:30:20,960
So they get closer and closer to Sioux city
airport.

385
00:30:20,960 --> 00:30:27,380
Under the very excellent guidance of Kevin.

386
00:30:27,380 --> 00:30:34,580
Who is a flight controller who moved to Sioux
City because he was at a busier airport and

387
00:30:34,580 --> 00:30:37,360
didn't like the stress.

388
00:30:37,360 --> 00:30:43,450
You are cleared to land on any runway.

389
00:30:43,450 --> 00:30:45,909
Haynes: Typical humor.

390
00:30:45,909 --> 00:30:53,190
You want to be particular and make it a runway?

391
00:30:53,190 --> 00:30:59,619
They line up for runway 22, a closed runway.

392
00:30:59,619 --> 00:31:02,840
You cannot see the whole of the runway from
the tower.

393
00:31:02,840 --> 00:31:09,640
It is also where they have all the emergency
equipment parked.

394
00:31:09,640 --> 00:31:14,950
They moved it out of the way.

395
00:31:14,950 --> 00:31:24,190
As they are coming in to land, it is incredible
as far as an airport.

396
00:31:24,190 --> 00:31:34,190
As they come in, a normal landing in a Dc
10 is 140 knots, 200 feet per minute.

397
00:31:34,190 --> 00:31:39,009
They are coming in at 215 knots, and increasing.

